questiontext.text:
The image below shows the Maxwell Model for viscoelastic materials, along with the displacement time plot obtained when a fixed load (F) is instantaneously applied, and later instantaneously removed.

In this system a spring (with spring constant 'k') is connected in series with a dashpot (with viscosity $$\small\eta$$).




From the options below, select which graph correctly represents what would happen if the spring constant of the spring was doubled, AND the viscosity in the dashpot was halved (represented by the green line).

(The black line represents the original conditions)

{1:MCV:~=


#Good Job!~


#Incorrect~


#Incorrect~


#Incorrect}

generalfeedback.text:
The image above shows the correct answer to this question.

There are two changes to note in this question:

1. The same force has been applied, but the spring constant has been doubled. Therefore, the displacement defined by the equation (F/k) has been halved.

2. The gradient of the sloped section of this graph represents the rate of displacement due to the dashpot, and is defined by (F/$$\small\eta$$). As the viscosity in the dashpot has been halved, the rate of displacement (and thus the gradient of the sloped section of the graph) has doubled.

hint.text: Which aspects of the graph will be affected by these changes?
